{"nodes":[{"pos":[12,51],"content":"ARM Exception Handling | Microsoft Docs","needQuote":false,"needEscape":true,"nodes":[{"content":"ARM Exception Handling | Microsoft Docs","pos":[0,39]}]},{"content":"ARM Exception Handling","pos":[531,553]},{"content":"Windows on ARM uses the same structured exception handling mechanism for asynchronous hardware-generated exceptions and synchronous software-generated exceptions.","pos":[554,716]},{"content":"Language-specific exception handlers are built on top of Windows structured exception handling by using language helper functions.","pos":[717,847]},{"content":"This document describes exception handling in Windows on ARM, and the language helpers used by code that's generated by MASM and the Visual C++ compiler.","pos":[848,1001]},{"content":"ARM Exception Handling","pos":[1010,1032]},{"content":"Windows on ARM uses <bpt id=\"p1\">*</bpt>unwind codes<ept id=\"p1\">*</ept> to control stack unwinding during <bpt id=\"p2\">[</bpt>structured exception handling<ept id=\"p2\">](http://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/desktop/ms680657)</ept> (SEH).","pos":[1036,1203],"source":"Windows on ARM uses *unwind codes* to control stack unwinding during [structured exception handling](http://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/desktop/ms680657) (SEH)."},{"content":"Unwind codes are a sequence of bytes stored in the .xdata section of the executable image.","pos":[1204,1294]},{"content":"They describe the operation of function prologue and epilogue code in an abstract way, so that the effects of a function’s prologue can be undone in preparation for unwinding to the caller’s stack frame.","pos":[1295,1498]},{"content":"The ARM EABI (embedded application binary interface) specifies an exception unwinding model that uses unwind codes, but it's not sufficient for SEH unwinding in Windows, which must handle asynchronous cases where the processor is in the middle of the prologue or epilogue of a function.","pos":[1505,1791]},{"content":"Windows also separates unwinding control into function-level unwinding and language-specific scope unwinding, which is unified in the ARM EABI.","pos":[1792,1935]},{"content":"For these reasons, Windows on ARM specifies more details for the unwinding data and procedure.","pos":[1936,2030]},{"content":"Assumptions","pos":[2040,2051]},{"content":"Executable images for Windows on ARM use the Portable Executable (PE) format.","pos":[2055,2132]},{"content":"For more information, see <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Microsoft PE and COFF Specification<ept id=\"p1\">](http://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/p/?linkid=84140)</ept>.","pos":[2133,2245],"source":" For more information, see [Microsoft PE and COFF Specification](http://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/p/?linkid=84140)."},{"content":"Exception handling information is stored in the .pdata and .xdata sections of the image.","pos":[2246,2334]},{"content":"The exception handling mechanism makes certain assumptions about code that follows the ABI for Windows on ARM:","pos":[2341,2451]},{"content":"When an exception occurs within the body of a function, it does not matter whether the prologue’s operations are undone, or the epilogue’s operations are performed in a forward manner.","pos":[2461,2645]},{"content":"Both should produce identical results.","pos":[2646,2684]},{"content":"Prologues and epilogues tend to mirror each other.","pos":[2694,2744]},{"content":"This can be used to reduce the size of the metadata needed to describe unwinding.","pos":[2745,2826]},{"content":"Functions tend to be relatively small.","pos":[2836,2874]},{"content":"Several optimizations rely on this for efficient packing of data.","pos":[2875,2940]},{"content":"If a condition is placed on an epilogue, it applies equally to each instruction in the epilogue.","pos":[2950,3046]},{"content":"If the stack pointer (SP) is saved in another register in the prologue, that register must remain unchanged throughout the function, so that the original SP may be recovered at any time.","pos":[3056,3242]},{"content":"Unless the SP is saved in another register, all manipulation of it must occur strictly within the prologue and epilogue.","pos":[3252,3372]},{"content":"To unwind any stack frame, these operations are required:","pos":[3382,3439]},{"content":"Adjust r13 (SP) in 4-byte increments.","pos":[3453,3490]},{"content":"Pop one or more integer registers.","pos":[3504,3538]},{"content":"Pop one or more VFP (virtual floating-point) registers.","pos":[3552,3607]},{"content":"Copy an arbitrary register value to r13 (SP).","pos":[3621,3666]},{"content":"Load SP from the stack by using a small post-decrement operation.","pos":[3680,3745]},{"content":"Parse one of a few well-defined frame types.","pos":[3759,3803]},{"content":".pdata Records","pos":[3813,3827]},{"content":"The .pdata records in a PE-format image are an ordered array of fixed-length items that describe every stack-manipulating function.","pos":[3831,3962]},{"content":"Leaf functions, which are functions that do not call other functions, don't require .pdata records when they don't manipulate the stack.","pos":[3963,4099]},{"content":"(That is, they don't require any local storage and don't have to save or restore non-volatile registers.).","pos":[4100,4206]},{"content":"Records for these functions can be omitted from the .pdata section to save space.","pos":[4207,4288]},{"content":"An unwind operation from one of these functions can just copy the return address from the Link Register (LR) to the program counter (PC) to move up to the caller.","pos":[4289,4451]},{"content":"Every .pdata record for ARM is 8 bytes long.","pos":[4458,4502]},{"content":"The general format of a record places the relative virtual address (RVA) of the function start in the first 32-bit word, followed by a second word that contains either a pointer to a variable-length .xdata block, or a packed word that describes a canonical function unwinding sequence, as shown in this table:","pos":[4503,4812]},{"content":"Word Offset","pos":[4819,4830]},{"content":"Bits","pos":[4831,4835]},{"content":"Purpose","pos":[4836,4843]},{"content":"0","pos":[4895,4896]},{"content":"0-31","pos":[4897,4901]},{"content":"is the 32-bit RVA of the start of the function.","pos":[4923,4970]},{"content":"If the function contains thumb code, the low bit of this address must be set.","pos":[4971,5048]},{"content":"1","pos":[5053,5054]},{"content":"0-1","pos":[5055,5058]},{"content":"is a 2-bit field that indicates how to interpret the remaining 30 bits of the second .pdata word.","pos":[5066,5163]},{"content":"If <ph id=\"ph1\">`Flag`</ph> is 0, then the remaining bits form an <ph id=\"ph2\">`Exception Information RVA`</ph> (with the low two bits implicitly 0).","pos":[5164,5277],"source":" If `Flag` is 0, then the remaining bits form an `Exception Information RVA` (with the low two bits implicitly 0)."},{"content":"If <ph id=\"ph1\">`Flag`</ph> is non-zero, then the remaining bits form a <ph id=\"ph2\">`Packed Unwind Data`</ph> structure.","pos":[5278,5363],"source":" If `Flag` is non-zero, then the remaining bits form a `Packed Unwind Data` structure."},{"content":"1","pos":[5368,5369]},{"content":"2-31","pos":[5370,5374]},{"content":"or <ph id=\"ph1\">`Packed Unwind Data`</ph>.","pos":[5403,5427],"source":" or `Packed Unwind Data`."},{"content":"is the address of the variable-length exception information structure, stored in the .xdata section.","pos":[5468,5568]},{"content":"This data must be 4-byte aligned.","pos":[5569,5602]},{"content":"is a compressed description of the operations required to unwind from a function, assuming a canonical form.","pos":[5636,5744]},{"content":"In this case, no .xdata record is required.","pos":[5745,5788]},{"content":"Packed Unwind Data","pos":[5799,5817]},{"content":"For functions whose prologues and epilogues follow the canonical form described below, packed unwind data can be used.","pos":[5821,5939]},{"content":"This eliminates the need for an .xdata record and significantly reduces the space required to provide unwind data.","pos":[5940,6054]},{"content":"The canonical prologues and epilogues are designed to meet the common requirements of a simple function that does not require an exception handler, and performs its setup and teardown operations in a standard order.","pos":[6055,6270]},{"content":"This table shows the format of a .pdata record that has packed unwind data:","pos":[6277,6352]},{"content":"Word Offset","pos":[6359,6370]},{"content":"Bits","pos":[6371,6375]},{"content":"Purpose","pos":[6376,6383]},{"content":"0","pos":[6435,6436]},{"content":"0-31","pos":[6437,6441]},{"content":"is the 32-bit RVA of the start of the function.","pos":[6463,6510]},{"content":"If the function contains thumb code, the low bit of this address must be set.","pos":[6511,6588]},{"content":"1","pos":[6593,6594]},{"content":"0-1","pos":[6595,6598]},{"content":"is a 2-bit field that has these meanings:","pos":[6606,6647]},{"content":"-   00 = packed unwind data not used; remaining bits point to .xdata record.","pos":[6660,6736]},{"content":"-   01 = packed unwind data.","pos":[6742,6770]},{"content":"-   10 = packed unwind data where the function is assumed to have no prologue.","pos":[6776,6854]},{"content":"This is useful for describing function fragments that are discontiguous with the start of the function.","pos":[6855,6958]},{"content":"-   11 = reserved.","pos":[6964,6982]},{"content":"1","pos":[6987,6988]},{"content":"2-12","pos":[6989,6993]},{"content":"is an 11-bit field that provides the length of the entire function in bytes divided by 2.","pos":[7012,7101]},{"content":"If the function is larger than 4K bytes, a full .xdata record must be used instead.","pos":[7102,7185]},{"content":"1","pos":[7190,7191]},{"content":"13-14","pos":[7192,7197]},{"content":"is a 2-bit field that indicates how the function returns:","pos":[7204,7261]},{"content":"-   00 = return via pop {pc} (the <ph id=\"ph1\">`L`</ph> flag bit must be set to 1 in this case).","pos":[7274,7352],"source":" -   00 = return via pop {pc} (the `L` flag bit must be set to 1 in this case)."},{"content":"-   01 = return by using a 16-bit branch.","pos":[7358,7399]},{"content":"-   10 = return by using a 32-bit branch.","pos":[7405,7446]},{"content":"-   11 = no epilogue at all.","pos":[7452,7480]},{"content":"This is useful for describing a discontiguous function fragment that may only contain a prologue, but whose epilogue is elsewhere.","pos":[7481,7611]},{"content":"1","pos":[7616,7617]},{"content":"15","pos":[7618,7620]},{"content":"is a 1-bit flag that indicates whether the function \"homes\" the integer parameter registers (r0-r3) by pushing them at the start of the function, and deallocates the 16 bytes of stack before returning.","pos":[7625,7826]},{"content":"(0 = does not home registers, 1 = homes registers.)","pos":[7827,7878]},{"content":"1","pos":[7883,7884]},{"content":"16-18","pos":[7885,7890]},{"content":"is a 3-bit field that indicates the index of the last saved non-volatile register.","pos":[7897,7979]},{"content":"If the <ph id=\"ph1\">`R`</ph> bit is 0, then only integer registers are being saved, and are assumed to be in the range of r4-rN, where N is equal to 4 + <ph id=\"ph2\">`Reg`</ph>.","pos":[7980,8121],"source":" If the `R` bit is 0, then only integer registers are being saved, and are assumed to be in the range of r4-rN, where N is equal to 4 + `Reg`."},{"content":"If the <ph id=\"ph1\">`R`</ph> bit is 1, then only floating-point registers are being saved, and are assumed to be in the range of d8-dN, where N is equal to 8 + <ph id=\"ph2\">`Reg`</ph>.","pos":[8122,8270],"source":" If the `R` bit is 1, then only floating-point registers are being saved, and are assumed to be in the range of d8-dN, where N is equal to 8 + `Reg`."},{"content":"The special combination of <ph id=\"ph1\">`R`</ph> = 1 and <ph id=\"ph2\">`Reg`</ph> = 7 indicates that no registers are saved.","pos":[8271,8358],"source":" The special combination of `R` = 1 and `Reg` = 7 indicates that no registers are saved."},{"content":"1","pos":[8363,8364]},{"content":"19","pos":[8365,8367]},{"content":"is a 1-bit flag that indicates whether the saved non-volatile registers are integer registers (0) or floating-point registers (1).","pos":[8372,8502]},{"content":"If <ph id=\"ph1\">`R`</ph> is set to 1 and the <ph id=\"ph2\">`Reg`</ph> field is set to 7, no non-volatile registers were pushed.","pos":[8503,8593],"source":" If `R` is set to 1 and the `Reg` field is set to 7, no non-volatile registers were pushed."},{"content":"1","pos":[8598,8599]},{"content":"20","pos":[8600,8602]},{"content":"is a 1-bit flag that indicates whether the function saves/restores LR, along with other registers indicated by the <ph id=\"ph1\">`Reg`</ph> field.","pos":[8607,8734],"source":" is a 1-bit flag that indicates whether the function saves/restores LR, along with other registers indicated by the `Reg` field."},{"content":"(0 = does not save/restore, 1 = does save/restore.)","pos":[8735,8786]},{"content":"1","pos":[8791,8792]},{"content":"21","pos":[8793,8795]},{"content":"is a 1-bit flag that indicates whether the function includes extra instructions to set up a frame chain for fast stack walking (1) or not (0).","pos":[8800,8942]},{"content":"If this bit is set, r11 is implicitly added to the list of integer non-volatile registers saved.","pos":[8943,9039]},{"content":"(See restrictions below if the <ph id=\"ph1\">`C`</ph> flag is used.)","pos":[9040,9089],"source":" (See restrictions below if the `C` flag is used.)"},{"content":"1","pos":[9094,9095]},{"content":"22-31","pos":[9096,9101]},{"content":"is a 10-bit field that indicates the number of bytes of stack that are allocated for this function, divided by 4.","pos":[9117,9230]},{"content":"However, only values between 0x000-0x3F3 can be directly encoded.","pos":[9231,9296]},{"content":"Functions that allocate more than 4044 bytes of stack must use a full .xdata reco