s.","pos":[17090,17193]},{"content":"The extension word that contains this field is only present if the <ph id=\"ph1\">`Epilogue Count`</ph> and <ph id=\"ph2\">`Code Words`</ph> fields in the first header word are both set to 0.","pos":[17194,17345],"source":" The extension word that contains this field is only present if the `Epilogue Count` and `Code Words` fields in the first header word are both set to 0."},{"content":"1","pos":[17354,17355]},{"content":"24-31","pos":[17356,17361]},{"content":"Reserved","pos":[17362,17370]},{"content":"After the exception data—if the <ph id=\"ph1\">`E`</ph> bit in the header was set to 0—is a list of information about epilogue scopes, which are packed one to a word and stored in order of increasing starting offset.","pos":[17381,17577],"source":"After the exception data—if the `E` bit in the header was set to 0—is a list of information about epilogue scopes, which are packed one to a word and stored in order of increasing starting offset."},{"content":"Each scope contains these fields:","pos":[17578,17611]},{"content":"Bits","pos":[17622,17626]},{"content":"Purpose","pos":[17627,17634]},{"content":"0-17","pos":[17676,17680]},{"pos":[17705,17828],"content":"is an 18-bit field that describes the offset of the epilogue, in bytes divided by 2, relative to the start of the function."},{"content":"18-19","pos":[17837,17842]},{"content":"is a 2-bit field reserved for future expansion.","pos":[17849,17896]},{"content":"Its value must be 0.","pos":[17897,17917]},{"content":"20-23","pos":[17926,17931]},{"content":"is a 4-bit field that gives the condition under which the epilogue is executed.","pos":[17944,18023]},{"content":"For unconditional epilogues, it should be set to 0xE, which indicates \"always\".","pos":[18024,18103]},{"content":"(An epilogue must be entirely conditional or entirely unconditional, and in Thumb-2 mode, the epilogue begins with the first instruction after the IT opcode.)","pos":[18104,18262]},{"content":"24-31","pos":[18271,18276]},{"pos":[18300,18402],"content":"is an 8-bit field that indicates the byte index of the first unwind code that describes this epilogue."},{"content":"After the list of epilogue scopes comes an array of bytes that contain unwind codes, which are described in detail in the Unwind Codes section in this article.","pos":[18413,18572]},{"content":"This array is padded at the end to the nearest full word boundary.","pos":[18573,18639]},{"content":"The bytes are stored in little-endian order so that they can be directly fetched in little-endian mode.","pos":[18640,18743]},{"content":"If the <ph id=\"ph1\">`X`</ph> field in the header is 1, the unwind code bytes are followed by the exception handler information.","pos":[18753,18862],"source":"If the `X` field in the header is 1, the unwind code bytes are followed by the exception handler information."},{"content":"This consists of one <ph id=\"ph1\">`Exception Handler RVA`</ph> that contains the address of the exception handler, followed immediately by the (variable-length) amount of data required by the exception handler.","pos":[18863,19055],"source":" This consists of one `Exception Handler RVA` that contains the address of the exception handler, followed immediately by the (variable-length) amount of data required by the exception handler."},{"content":"The .xdata record is designed so that it is possible to fetch the first 8 bytes and compute the full size of the record, not including the length of the variable-sized exception data that follows.","pos":[19062,19258]},{"content":"This code snippet computes the record size:","pos":[19259,19302]},{"content":"Athough the prologue and each epilogue has an index into the unwind codes, the table is shared between them.","pos":[19940,20048]},{"content":"It is not uncommon that they can all share the same unwind codes.","pos":[20049,20114]},{"content":"We recommend that compiler writers optimize for this case, because the largest index that can be specified is 255, and that limits the total number of unwind codes possible for a particular function.","pos":[20115,20314]},{"content":"Unwind Codes","pos":[20324,20336]},{"content":"The array of unwind codes is a pool of instruction sequences that describe exactly how to undo the effects of the prologue, in the order in which the operations must be undone.","pos":[20340,20516]},{"content":"The unwind codes are a mini instruction set, encoded as a string of bytes.","pos":[20517,20591]},{"content":"When execution is complete, the return address to the calling function is in the LR register, and all non-volatile registers are restored to their values at the time the function was called.","pos":[20592,20782]},{"content":"If exceptions were guaranteed to only ever occur within a function body, and never within a prologue or epilogue, then only one unwind sequence would be necessary.","pos":[20789,20952]},{"content":"However, the Windows unwinding model requires an ability to unwind from within a partially executed prologue or epilogue.","pos":[20953,21074]},{"content":"To accommodate this requirement, the unwind codes have been carefully designed to have an unambiguous one-to-one mapping to each relevant opcode in the prologue and epilogue.","pos":[21075,21249]},{"content":"This has several implications:","pos":[21250,21280]},{"content":"It is possible to compute the length of the prologue and epilogue by counting the number of unwind codes.","pos":[21290,21395]},{"content":"This is possible even with variable-length Thumb-2 instructions because there are distinct mappings for 16-bit and 32-bit opcodes.","pos":[21396,21526]},{"content":"By counting the number of instructions past the start of an epilogue scope, it is possible to skip the equivalent number of unwind codes, and execute the rest of a sequence to complete the partially-executed unwind that the epilogue was performing.","pos":[21536,21784]},{"content":"By counting the number of instructions before the end of the prologu