8,24350]},{"content":"end + 16-bit nop in epilogue","pos":[24351,24379]},{"content":"FE","pos":[24384,24386]},{"content":"32","pos":[24390,24392]},{"content":"end + 32-bit nop in epilogue","pos":[24393,24421]},{"content":"FF","pos":[24426,24428]},{"content":"end","pos":[24434,24437]},{"content":"This shows the range of hexadecimal values for each byte in an unwind code <ph id=\"ph1\">`Code`</ph>, along with the opcode size <ph id=\"ph2\">`Opsize`</ph> and the corresponding original instruction interpretation.","pos":[24445,24622],"source":"This shows the range of hexadecimal values for each byte in an unwind code `Code`, along with the opcode size `Opsize` and the corresponding original instruction interpretation."},{"content":"Empty cells indicate shorter unwind codes.","pos":[24623,24665]},{"content":"In instructions that have large values covering multiple bytes, the most significant bits are stored first.","pos":[24666,24773]},{"content":"The <ph id=\"ph1\">`Opsize`</ph> field shows the implicit opcode size associated with each Thumb-2 operation.","pos":[24774,24863],"source":" The `Opsize` field shows the implicit opcode size associated with each Thumb-2 operation."},{"content":"The apparent duplicate entries in the table with different encodings are used to distinguish between different opcode sizes.","pos":[24864,24988]},{"content":"The unwind codes are designed so that the first byte of the code tells both the total size in bytes of the code and the size of the corresponding opcode in the instruction stream.","pos":[24995,25174]},{"content":"To compute the size of the prologue or epilogue, walk the unwind codes from the start of the sequence to the end, and use a lookup table or similar method to determine how long the corresponding opcode is.","pos":[25175,25380]},{"content":"Unwind codes 0xFD and 0xFE are equivalent to the regular end code 0xFF, but account for one extra nop opcode in the epilogue case, either 16-bit or 32-bit.","pos":[25387,25542]},{"content":"For prologues, codes 0xFD, 0xFE and 0xFF are exactly equivalent.","pos":[25543,25607]},{"content":"This accounts for the common epilogue endings <ph id=\"ph1\">`bx lr`</ph> or <ph id=\"ph2\">`b &lt;tailcall-target&gt;`</ph>, which don’t have an equivalent prologue instruction.","pos":[25608,25740],"source":" This accounts for the common epilogue endings `bx lr` or `b <tailcall-target>`, which don’t have an equivalent prologue instruction."},{"content":"This increases the chance that unwind sequences can be shared between the prologue and the epilogues.","pos":[25741,25842]},{"content":"In many cases, it should be possible to use the same set of unwind codes for the prologue and all epilogues.","pos":[25849,25957]},{"content":"However, to handle the unwinding of partially executed prologues and epilogues, you might have to have multiple unwind code sequences that vary in ordering or behavior.","pos":[25958,26126]},{"content":"This is why each epilogue has its own index into the unwind array to show where to begin executing.","pos":[26127,26226]},{"content":"Unwinding Partial Prologues and Epilogues","pos":[26236,26277]},{"content":"The most common unwinding case is when the exception occurs in the body of the function, away from the prologue and all epilogues.","pos":[26281,26411]},{"content":"In this case, the unwinder executes the codes in the unwind array beginning at index 0 and continues until an end opcode is detected.","pos":[26412,26545]},{"content":"When an exception occurs while a prologue or epilogue is executing, the stack frame is only partially constructed, and the unwinder must determine exactly what has been done in order to correctly undo it.","pos":[26552,26756]},{"content":"For example, consider this prologue and epilogue sequence:","pos":[26763,26821]},{"content":"Next to each opcode is the appropriate unwind code to describe this operation.","pos":[27102,27180]},{"content":"The sequence of unwind codes for the prologue is a mirror image of the unwind codes for the epilogue, not counting the final instruction.","pos":[27181,27318]},{"content":"This case is common, and is the reason the unwind codes for the prologue are always assumed to be stored in reverse order from the prologue’s execution order.","pos":[27319,27477]},{"content":"This gives us a common set of unwind codes:","pos":[27478,27521]},{"content":"The 0xFD code is a special code for the end of the sequence that means that the epilogue is one 16-bit instruction longer than the prologue.","pos":[27568,27708]},{"content":"This makes greater sharing of unwind codes possible.","pos":[27709,27761]},{"content":"In the example, if an exception occurs while the function body between the prologue and epilogue is executing, unwinding starts with the epilogue case, at offset 0 within the epilogue code.","pos":[27768,27957]},{"content":"This corresponds to offset 0x140 in the example.","pos":[27958,28006]},{"content":"The unwinder executes the full unwind sequence, because no cleanup has been done.","pos":[28007,28088]},{"content":"If instead the exception occurs one instruction after the beginning of the epilogue code, the unwinder can successfully unwind by skipping the first unwind code.","pos":[28089,28250]},{"content":"Given a one-to-one mapping between opcodes and unwind codes, if unwinding from instruction <bpt id=\"p1\">*</bpt>n<ept id=\"p1\">*</ept> in the epilogue, the unwinder should skip the first <bpt id=\"p2\">*</bpt>n<ept id=\"p2\">*</ept> unwind codes.","pos":[28251,28415],"source":" Given a one-to-one mapping between opcodes and unwind codes, if unwinding from instruction *n* in the epilogue, the unwinder should skip the first *n* unwind codes."},{"content":"Similar logic works in reverse for the prologue.","pos":[28422,28470]},{"content":"If unwinding from offset 0 in the prologue, nothing has to be executed.","pos":[28471,28542]},{"content":"If unwinding from one instruction in, the unwind sequence should start one unwind code from the end because prologue unwind codes are stored in reverse order.","pos":[28543,28701]},{"content":"In the general case, if unwinding from instruction <bpt id=\"p1\">*</bpt>n<ept id=\"p1\">*</ept> in the prologue, unwinding should start executing at <bpt id=\"p2\">*</bpt>n<ept id=\"p2\">*</ept> unwind codes from the end of the list of codes.","pos":[28702,28861],"source":" In the general case, if unwinding from instruction *n* in the prologue, unwinding should start executing at *n* unwind codes from the end of the list of codes."},{"content":"Prologue and epilogue unwind codes do not always match exactly.","pos":[28868,28931]},{"content":"In that case, the unwind code array may have to contain several sequences of codes.","pos":[28932,29015]},{"content":"To determine the offset to begin processing codes, use this logic:","pos":[29016,29082]},{"content":"If unwinding from within the body of the function, begin executing unwind codes at index 0 and continue until an end opcode is reached.","pos":[29092,29227]},{"content":"If unwinding from within an epilogue, use the epilogue-specific starting index provided by the epilogue scope.","pos":[29237,29347]},{"content":"Calculate how many bytes the PC is from the start of the epilogue.","pos":[29348,29414]},{"content":"Skip forward through the unwind codes until all of the already-executed instructions are accounted for.","pos":[29415,29518]},{"content":"Execute the unwind sequence starting at that point.","pos":[29519,29570]},{"content":"If unwinding from within the prologue, start from index 0 in the unwind codes.","pos":[29580,29658]},{"content":"Calculate the length of the prologue code from the sequence, and then calculate how many bytes the PC is from the end of the prologue.","pos":[29659,29793]},{"content":"Skip forward through the unwind codes until all of the unexecuted instructions are accounted for.","pos":[29794,29891]},{"content":"Execute the unwind sequence starting at that point.","pos":[29892,29943]},{"content":"The unwind codes for the prologue must always be the first in the array.","pos":[29950,30022]},{"content":"They are also the codes used to unwind in the general case of unwinding from within the body.","pos":[30023,30116]},{"content":"Any epilogue-specific code sequences should follow immediately after the prologue code sequence.","pos":[30117,30213]},{"content":"Function Fragments","pos":[30223,30241]},{"content":"For code optimization, it may be useful to split a function into discontiguous parts.","pos":[30245,30330]},{"content":"When this is done, each function fragment requires its own separate .pdata—and possibly .xdata—record.","pos":[30331,30433]},{"content":"Assuming that the function prologue is at the beginning of the function and can't be split, there are four function fragment cases:","pos":[30440,30571]},{"content":"Prologue only; all epilogues in other fragments.","pos":[30581,30629]},{"content":"Prologue and one or more epilogues; additional epilogues in other fragments.","pos":[30639,30715]},{"content":"No prologue or epilogues; prologue and one or more epilogues in other fragments.","pos":[30725,30805]},{"content":"Epilogues only; prologue and possibly additional epilogues in other fragments.","pos":[30815,30893]},{"content":"In the first case, only the prologue must be described.","pos":[30900,30955]},{"content":"This can be done in compact .pdata form by describing the prologue normally and specifying a <ph id=\"ph1\">`Ret`</ph> value of 3 to indicate no epilogue.","pos":[30956,31090],"source":" This can be done in compact .pdata form by describing the prologue normally and specifying a `Ret` value of 3 to indicate no epilogue."},{"content":"In the full .xdata form, this can be done by providing the prologue unwind codes at index 0 as usual, and specifying an epilogue count of 0.","pos":[31091,31231]},{"content":"The second case is just like a normal function.","pos":[31238,31285]},{"content":"If there’s only one epilogue in the fragment, and it is at the end of the fragment, then a compact .pdata record can be used.","pos":[31286,31411]},{"content":"Otherwise, a full .xdata record must be used.","pos":[31412,31457]},{"content":"Keep in mind that the offsets specified for the epilogue start are relative to the start of the fragment, not the original start of the function.","pos":[31458,31603]},{"content":"The third and fourth cases are variants of the first and second cases, respectively, except they don’t contain a prologue.","pos":[31610,31732]},{"content":"In these situations, it is assumed that there is code before the start of the epilogue and it is considered part of the body of the function, which would normally be unwound by undoing the effects of the prologue.","pos":[31733,31946]},{"content":"These cases must therefore be encoded with a pseudo-prologue, which describes how to unwind from within the body, but which is treated as 0-length when determining whether to perform a partial unwind at the start of the fragment.","pos":[31947,32176]},{"content":"Alternatively, this pseudo-prologue may be described by using the same unwind codes as the epilogue because they presumably perform equivalent operations.","pos":[32177,32331]},{"content":"In the third and fourth cases, the presence of a pseudo-prologue is specified either by setting the <ph id=\"ph1\">`Flag`</ph> field of the compact .pdata record to 2, or by setting the <ph id=\"ph2\">`F`</ph> flag in the .xdata header to 1.","pos":[32338,32539],"source":"In the third and fourth cases, the presence of a pseudo-prologue is specified either by setting the `Flag` field of the compact .pdata record to 2, or by setting the `F` flag in the .xdata header to 1."},{"content":"In either case, the check for a partial prologue unwind is ignored, and all non-epilogue unwinds are considered to be full.","pos":[32540,32663]},{"content":"Large Functions","pos":[32674,32689]},{"content":"Fragments can be used to describe functions larger than the 512 KB limit imposed by the bit fields in the .xdata header.","pos":[32693,32813]},{"content":"To describe a very large function, just break it into fragments smaller than 512 KB.","pos":[32814,32898]},{"content":"Each fragment should be adjusted so that it does not split an epilogue into multiple pieces.","pos":[32899,32991]},{"content":"Only the first fragment of the function contains a prologue; all other fragments are marked as having no prologue.","pos":[32998,33112]},{"content":"Depending on the number of epilogues, each fragment may contain zero or more epilogues.","pos":[33113,33200]},{"content":"Keep in mind that each epilogue scope in a fragment specifies its starting offset relative to the start of the fragment, not the start of the function.","pos":[33201,33352]},{"content":"If a fragment has no prologue and no epilogue, it still requires its own .pdata—and possibly .xdata—record to describe how to unwind from within the body of the function.","pos":[33359,33529]},{"content":"Shrink-wrapping","pos":[33540,33555]},{"content":"A more complex special case of function fragments is <bpt id=\"p1\">*</bpt>shrink-wrapping<ept id=\"p1\">*</ept>, a technique for deferring register saves from the start of the function to later in the function, to optimize for simple cases that don’t require register saving.","pos":[33559,33793],"source":"A more complex special case of function fragments is *shrink-wrapping*, a technique for deferring register saves from the start of the function to later in the function, to optimize for simple cases that don’t require register saving."},{"content":"This can be described as an outer region that allocates the stack space but saves a minimal set of registers, and an inner region that saves and restores additional registers.","pos":[33794,33969]},{"content":"Shrink-wrapped functions are typically expected to pre-allocate the space for the extra register saves in the regular prologue, and then perform the register saves by using <ph id=\"ph1\">`str`</ph> or <ph id=\"ph2\">`stm`</ph> instead of <ph id=\"ph3\">`push`</ph>.","pos":[34570,34776],"source":"Shrink-wrapped functions are typically expected to pre-allocate the space for the extra register saves in the regular prologue, and then perform the register saves by using `str` or `stm` instead of `push`."},{"content":"This keeps all stack-pointer manipulation in the function’s original prologue.","pos":[34777,34855]},{"content":"The example shrink-wrapped function must be broken into three regions, which are marked as A, B, and C in the comments.","pos":[34862,34981]},{"content":"The first A region covers the start of the function through the end of the additional non-volatile saves.","pos":[34982,35087]},{"content":"A .pdata or .xdata record must be constructed to describe this fragment as having a prologue and no epilogues.","pos":[35088,35198]},{"content":"The middle B region gets its own .pdata or .xdata record that describes a fragment that has no prologue and no epilogue.","pos":[35205,35325]},{"content":"However, the unwind codes for this region must still be present because it's considered a function body.","pos":[35326,35430]},{"content":"The codes must describe a composite prologue that represents both the original registers saved in the region-A prologue and the additional registers saved before entering region B, as if they were produced by one sequence of operations.","pos":[35431,35667]},{"content":"The register saves for region B can't be considered as an \"inner prologue\" because the composite prologue described for region B must describe both the region-A prologue and the additional registers saved.","pos":[35674,35879]},{"content":"If fragment B were described as having a prologue, the unwind codes would also imply the size of that prologue, and there is no way to describe the composite prologue in a way that maps one-to-one with the opcodes that only save the additional registers.","pos":[35880,36134]},{"content":"The additional register saves must be considered part of region A, because until they are complete, the composite prologue does not accurately describe the state of the stack.","pos":[36141,36316]},{"content":"The last C region gets its own .pdata or .xdata record, describing a fragment that has no prologue but does have an epilogue.","pos":[36323,36448]},{"content":"An alternative approach can also work if the stack manipulation done before entering region B can be reduced to one instruction:","pos":[36455,36583]},{"content":"The key here is that on each instruction boundary, the stack is fully consistent with the unwind codes for the region.","pos":[37093,37211]},{"content":"If an unwind occurs before the inner push in this example, it is considered part of region A, and only the region A prologue is unwound.","pos":[37212,37348]},{"content":"If the unwind occurs after the inner push, it is considered part of region B, which has no prologue, but has unwind codes that describe both the inner push and the original prologue from region A. Similar logic holds for the inner pop.","pos":[37349,37584]},{"content":"Encoding Optimizations","pos":[37594,37616]},{"content":"Due to the richness of the unwind codes and the ability to leverage compact and expanded forms of data, there are many opportunities to optimize the encoding to further reduce space.","pos":[37620,37802]},{"content":"With aggressive use of these techniques, the net overhead of describing functions and fragments by using unwind codes can be quite minimal.","pos":[37803,37942]},{"content":"The most important optimization is to be careful not to confuse prologue/epilogue boundaries for unwinding purposes with logical prologue/epilogue boundaries from a compiler perspective.","pos":[37949,38135]},{"content":"The unwinding boundaries can be shrunk and made tighter to improve efficiency.","pos":[38136,38214]},{"content":"For example, a prologue may contain code after the stack setup to perform additional verification checks.","pos":[38215,38320]},{"content":"But once all the stack manipulation is complete, there is no need to encode further operations, and anything beyond that can be removed from the unwinding prologue.","pos":[38321,38485]},{"content":"This same rule applies to the function length.","pos":[38492,38538]},{"content":"If there is data—for example, a literal pool—that follows an epilogue in a function, it should not be included as part of the function length.","pos":[38539,38681]},{"content":"By shrinking the function to just the code that is part of the function, the chances are much greater that the epilogue will be at the very end and a compact.","pos":[38682,38840]},{"content":"pdata record can be used.","pos":[38841,38866]},{"content":"In a prologue, once the stack pointer is saved to another register, there is typically no need to record any further opcodes.","pos":[38873,38998]},{"content":"To unwind the function, the first thing that's done is to recover SP from the saved register, and so further operations do not have any impact on the unwind.","pos":[38999,39156]},{"content":"Single-instruction epilogues do not have to be encoded at all, either as scopes or as unwind codes.","pos":[39163,39262]},{"content":"If an unwind takes place before that instruction is executed, then it can be assumed to be from within the body of the function, and just executing the prologue unwind codes is sufficient.","pos":[39263,39451]},{"content":"If the unwind takes place after the single instruction is executed, then by definition it takes place in another region.","pos":[39452,39572]},{"content":"Multi-instruction epilogues do not have to encode the first instruction of the epilogue, for the same reason as the previous point: if the unwind takes place before that instruction executes, a full prologue unwind is sufficient.","pos":[39579,39808]},{"content":"If the unwind takes place after that instruction, then only the subsequent operations have to be considered.","pos":[39809,39917]},{"content":"Unwind code re-use should be aggressive.","pos":[39924,39964]},{"content":"The index specified by each epilogue scope points to an arbitrary starting point in the array of unwind codes.","pos":[39965,40075]},{"content":"It does not have to point to the start of a previous sequence; it can point in the middle.","pos":[40076,40166]},{"content":"The best approach here is to generate the desired code sequence and then scan for an exact byte match in the already-encoded pool of sequences and use any perfect match as a starting point for re-use.","pos":[40167,40367]},{"content":"If, after single-instruction epilogues are ignored, there are no remaining epilogues, consider using a compact .pdata form; it becomes much more likely in the absence of an epilogue.","pos":[40374,40556]},{"content":"Examples","pos":[40565,40573]},{"content":"In these examples, the image base is at 0x00400000.","pos":[40577,40628]},{"content":"Example 1: Leaf Function, No Locals","pos":[40638,40673]},{"content":".pdata (fixed, 2 words):","pos":[40846,40870]},{"content":"Word 0","pos":[40880,40886]},{"pos":[40921,40959],"content":"= 0x000535F8 (= 0x004535F8–0x00400000)"},{"content":"Word 1","pos":[40969,40975]},{"pos":[40996,41051],"content":"= 1, indicating canonical prologue and epilogue formats"},{"pos":[41083,41100],"content":"= 0x31 (= 0x62/2)"},{"pos":[41120,41158],"content":"= 1, indicating a 16-bit branch return"},{"pos":[41176,41221],"content":"= 0, indicating the parameters were not homed"},{"pos":[41238,41284],"content":"=0 and <ph id=\"ph1\">`Reg`</ph> = 1, indicating push/pop of r4-r5","source":"=0 and `Reg` = 1, indicating push/pop of r4-r5"},{"pos":[41302,41336],"content":"= 0, indicating no LR save/restore"},{"pos":[41354,41387],"content":"= 0, indicating no frame chaining"},{"pos":[41416,41451],"content":"= 0, indicating no stack adjustment"},{"content":"Example 2: Nested Function with Local Allocation","pos":[41461,41509]},{"content":".pdata (fixed, 2 words):","pos":[41749,41